President Obama announced his intent to nominate David S. Cohen as the Under Secretary for Terrorism and Financial Crimes at the Department of the Treasury. Cohen, who was confirmed by the United States Senate in 2009, has experience in counterterrorist financing and anti-money laundering efforts. He previously worked as a partner at the law firm WilmerHale, focusing on civil litigation, criminal defense, internal investigations, and anti-money laundering counseling. Cohen also served at the Treasury Department and received the Treasury Secretary's Award for outstanding service. He holds a J.D. from Yale Law School and a B.A. from Cornell University.

President Obama also announced his intent to nominate Donald B. Verrilli, Jr. as the Solicitor General of the United States at the Department of Justice. Verrilli currently serves as a Deputy Counsel to the President and previously worked in the Department of Justice as an Associate Deputy Attorney General, focusing on domestic and national security policy issues. Before joining the Justice Department, Verrilli was a litigator at the Jenner & Block law firm for over 20 years, specializing in First Amendment, telecommunications, and intellectual property law. He has participated in over 100 cases before the Supreme Court, arguing twelve of them, and has been involved in approximately 90 cases in U.S. Courts of Appeal and state supreme courts. Verrilli also held leadership positions at Jenner & Block and served as an adjunct professor of constitutional law at Georgetown University Law Center. He received his J.D. from Columbia Law School and a B.A. from Yale University.